{{distinguish|Haldane's principle}}
[[File:Human male karyotpe high resolution - XY chromosome cropped.JPG|thumb|In humans, barring intersex conditions and other unusual states, it is the male that is [[heterogametic]], with XY sex chromosomes.]]
'''Haldane's rule''' is an observation about the early stage of [[speciation]], formulated in 1922 by the British [[evolutionary biology|evolutionary biologist]] [[J.B.S. Haldane]], that states that if in a [[species]] [[hybrid (biology)|hybrid]] only one sex is inviable or [[Sterility (physiology)|sterile]], that sex is more likely to be the [[heterogametic sex]]. The heterogametic sex is the one with two different [[sex chromosome]]s; in [[theria|therian mammals]],{{refn|group=note|Monotremes have more than two. The [[platypus]] has five pairs, as do female [[echidna]]s. Male echidnas have nine.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Deakin |first1=J.E. |last2=Graves |first2=J.A.M. |last3=Rens |first3=W. |title=The Evolution of Marsupial and Monotreme Chromosomes |journal=Cytogenetic and Genome Research |volume=137 |issue=2–4 |year=2012 |pages=113–129 |doi=10.1159/000339433}}</ref>}} for example, this is the male.<ref name="genetics">{{cite journal |title=The Dominance Theory of Haldane's Rule|author=Turelli, M; Orr, H.A. |journal=[[Genetics (journal)|Genetics]] |date=May 1995 |volume=140 |issue=1 |pp=389–402 |pmc=1206564 |pmid=7635302}}</ref>

==Overview==
Haldane himself described the rule as:
{{quote|When in the [[F1 hybrid|F1]] offspring of two different animal races one sex is absent, rare, or sterile, that sex is the heterozygous sex (heterogametic sex).<ref name=Haldane1922>{{cite journal| doi=10.1007/BF02983075| last1=Haldane| first1=J. B. S.| year=1922| title=Sex ratio and unisexual sterility in hybrid animals| journal=[[Journal of Genetics|J. Genet.]]| volume=12| pages=101–109 }}</ref>}}

Haldane's rule applies to the vast majority of heterogametic organisms. This includes the case where two species make secondary contact in an area of [[sympatry]] and form hybrids after [[allopatric speciation]] has occurred.

The rule includes both male heterogametic ([[XY sex-determination system|XY]] or [[XO sex-determination system|XO-type sex determination]], such as found in [[mammal]]s and ''[[Drosophila]]'' fruit flies) and female heterogametic ([[ZW sex-determination system|ZW-type sex determination]], as found in [[birds]] and [[butterflies]]), and some [[Dioecy|dioecious]] plants such as [[Silene|campions]].<ref name="Brothers2010">{{cite journal | doi=10.1111/j.1558-5646.2010.01095.x| last1=Brothers| first1=Amanda N.| last2=Delph| first2=Lynda F.| year=2010| title=Haldane's rule is extended to plants with sex chromosomes| journal=Evolution| volume=64| issue=12| pages=3643–3648 | pmid=20681984}}</ref>

Hybrid dysfunction (sterility and inviability) is a major form of post-[[zygote|zygotic]] reproductive isolation, which occurs in early stages of speciation. Evolution can produce a similar pattern of isolation in a vast array of different organisms. However, the actual mechanisms leading to Haldane's rule in different taxa remain largely undefined.

==Hypotheses==
Many different hypotheses have been advanced to address the evolutionary mechanisms to produce Haldane's rule. Currently, the most popular explanation for Haldane's rule is the composite hypothesis, which divides Haldane's rule into multiple subdivisions, including sterility, inviability, male heterogamety, and female heterogamety. The composite hypothesis states that Haldane's rule in different subdivisions has different causes. Individual genetic mechanisms may not be mutually exclusive, and these mechanisms may act together to cause Haldane's rule in any given subdivision.<ref name=Orrl1993>{{cite journal | last1=Orr | first1=H. A. | year=1993 | title=Haldane's rule has multiple genetic causes | journal=Nature | volume=361 | issue=6412 | pages=532–533 | url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v361/n6412/pdf/361532a0.pdf | doi=10.1038/361532a0 | pmid=8429905}}</ref><ref name=Wul1993>{{cite journal | last1=Wu | first1=C.-I. | last2=Davis | first2=A. W. | year=1993 | title=Evolution of postmating reproductive isolation: the composite nature of Haldane's rule and its genetic bases | journal=The American Naturalist | volume=142 | issue=22 | pages=187–212 | jstor=2462812 | doi= 10.1086/285534 | pmid=19425975}}</ref> In contrast to these views that emphasise genetic mechanisms, another view hypothesizes that population dynamics during population divergence may cause Haldane's rule.<ref name=Wangl2003>{{cite journal | last1=Wang | first1=R. | year=2003 | title=Differential strength of sex-biased hybrid inferiority in impeding gene flow may be a cause of Haldane's rule | journal=Journal of Evolutionary Biology | volume=16 | pmid=14635874 | issue=2 | pages=353–361 | url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1046/j.1420-9101.2003.00528.x/pdf | doi=10.1046/j.1420-9101.2003.00528.x}}</ref>

The main genetic hypotheses are:

* Dominance: Heterogametic hybrids are affected by all X-linked alleles (be they recessive or dominant) causing incompatibilities due to divergent alleles being brought together. However, homogametic hybrids are only affected by dominant deleterious X-linked alleles. Heterogametic hybrids, which carry only a single copy of a given [[X-linked]] gene, will be affected by mutations regardless of dominance. Thus, an X-linked incompatibility between diverging populations is more likely to be expressed in the heterogametic sex than in the homogametic sex.
* The "faster male": Male genes are thought to evolve faster due to [[sexual selection]].<ref name=Wul1993 /> As a result, male sterility becomes more evident in male heterogametic taxa (XY sex determination). This hypothesis conflicts with Haldane's rule in male homogametic taxa, in which females are more affected by hybrid inferiority. It therefore only applies to male sterility in taxa with XY sex determination, according to the composite theory.
* [[Meiotic drive]]: In hybrid populations, selfish genetic elements inactivate sperm cells (i.e.: an X-linked drive factor inactivates a Y-bearing sperm and vice versa).
* The "faster X": Genes on hemizygous chromosomes may evolve more quickly by enhancing selection on possible recessive alleles causing a larger effect in reproductive isolation.<ref name=Charlesworth1987>{{cite journal | last1=Charlesworth | first1=B. | last2=Coyne | first2=J. A. | last3=Barton | first3=N. H. | year=1987 | title=The relative rates of evolution of sex chromosomes and autosomes | journal=The American Naturalist | volume=130 | issue=1 | pages=113–146 | jstor=10.2307/2461884 | doi=10.1086/284701}}</ref>  
* Differential selection: Hybrid incompatibilities affecting the heterogametic sex and homogametic sex are fundamentally different isolating mechanisms, which makes heterogametic inferiority (sterility/inviability) more visible or preserved in nature.<ref name="Wangl2003"/>

Data from multiple phylogenetic groups support a combination of dominance and faster X-chromosome theories.<ref name=Schilthuizen2011>{{cite journal| last1=Schilthuizen | first1=M. | last2=Giesbers| first2= M. C.| last3=Beukeboom | first3= L. W.| year=2011| title=Haldane's rule in the 21st century| journal=Heredity| volume=107| pages=95–102| doi=10.1038/hdy.2010.170 | issue=2 | pmid=21224879 | pmc=3178397}}</ref> However, it has recently been argued that dominance theory can not explain Haldane's rule in marsupials since both sexes experience the same incompatibilities due to paternal [[X-inactivation]] in females.<ref name="Watson2012">{{cite journal | last1=Watson | first1=E. | last2=Demuth | first2=J. | year=2012 | title=Haldane's rule in marsupials: what happens when both sexes are functionally hemizygous? | journal=Journal of Heredity | volume=103 | issue=3 | pages=453–458 | doi=10.1093/jhered/esr154 | pmid=22378959 | pmc=3331990}}</ref>

The dominance hypothesis is the core of the composite theory, and X-linked recessive/dominance effects have been demonstrated in many cases to cause hybrid incompatibilities. There is also supporting evidence for the faster male and meiotic drive hypotheses. For example, a significant reduction of male-driven gene flow is observed in [[Asian elephant]]s, suggesting faster evolution of male traits.<ref name=Fickel2007>{{cite journal | last1=Fickel | first1=J. | last2=Lieckfeldt | first2= D. | last3=Ratanakorn | first3=P. | last4=Pitra | first4=C. | year=2007 | title=Distribution of haplotypes and microsatellite alleles among Asian elephants (''Elephas maximus'') in Thailand | journal=European Journal of Wildlife Research | volume=53 | issue=4 | pages=298–303 | url=http://www.springerlink.com/index/R0Q2143R8852824N.pdf | doi=10.1007/s10344-007-0099-x}}</ref>

Although the rule was initially stated in context of [[diploid]] organisms with chromosomal [[Sex-determination system|sex determination]], it has recently been argued that it can be extended to certain species lacking chromosomal sex determination, such as [[haplodiploids]]<ref name="Koevoets2009">{{cite journal | last1=Koevoets | first1=T. | last2=Beukeboom | first2=L. W. | year=2009 | title=Genetics of postzygotic isolation and Haldane's rule in haplodiploids | journal=Heredity | volume=102 | issue=1 | pages=16–23 | url=http://www.nature.com/hdy/journal/v102/n1/abs/hdy200844a.html | doi=10.1038/hdy.2008.44 | pmid=18523445}}</ref> and [[hermaphrodites]].<ref name="Schilthuizen2011"/>

==Exceptions==
There are notable exceptions to Haldane's rule, where the homogametic sex turns out to be inviable while the heterogametic sex is viable and fertile. This is seen in ''[[Drosophila]]'' fruit flies.<ref name=SawamuraK1996>{{cite journal | last1 = Sawamura | first1 = K. | year = 1996 | title = Maternal effect as a cause of exceptions for Haldane's rule | journal = Genetics | volume = 143 | issue = 1 | pages = 609–611 | pmid = 8722809 | pmc = 1207293}}</ref><ref name="Ferree2009">{{cite journal | last1 = Ferree | first1 = Patrick M. | last2 = Barbash | first2 = Daniel A. | editor1-last = Noor | editor1-first = Mohamed A. F. | year = 2009 | title = Species-Specific Heterochromatin Prevents Mitotic Chromosome Segregation to Cause Hybrid Lethality in ''Drosophila'' | journal = PLOS Biology | volume = 7 | issue = 10 | url = http://www.plosbiology.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pbio.1000234 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pbio.1000234 | pmid = 19859525 | pages = e1000234 | pmc = 2760206}}</ref>

