{{Orphan|date=April 2016}}
The view that people can add value to their lives by creating and maintaining a personal narrative.<ref>{{Cite book | publisher = Oxford University Press | last = Kenyon | first = Gary |author2=Ernst Bohlmeijer |author3=William L. Randall | title = Storying later life: Issues, investigations, and interventions in narrative gerontology | accessdate = 2014-03-05 | year = 2010 | url = https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=iscrccRn764C&oi=fnd&pg=PR5&dq=+narrative+gerontology&ots=o4MCS6Ml1C&sig=6sEtgfyrYdzIgrsdH3qDsVQTvTA }}</ref> Narrative gerontology is consistent with theories of aging.<ref>{{Cite journal | pages = 40 | last = Kenyan | first = Gary M. |author2=Jan-Eric Ruth |author3=Wilhelm Mader | title = Elements of a narrative gerontology | journal = Handbook of theories of aging | accessdate = 2014-03-05 | year = 1999 | url = https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=7qpHuXKsaC0C&oi=fnd&pg=PA40&dq=+narrative+gerontology&ots=FQT7REkpt6&sig=3ukLulcgDV2skaO6dmxG8Lxaw6Y }}</ref>
Gerontological narratives are organized around a number of themes, such as time, story and wisdom.<ref>{{Cite journal | volume = 23 | issue = 04 | pages = 333–346 | last = Randall | first = William L. |author2=Gary M. Kenyon | title = Time, story, and wisdom: Emerging themes in narrative gerontology | journal = Canadian Journal on Aging/La Revue canadienne du vieillissement | accessdate = 2014-03-05 | year = 2004 | url = http://journals.cambridge.org/abstract_S0714980800003366 | doi=10.1353/cja.2005.0027 }}</ref> Research suggests that the richer the story the more resilient the person.<ref>{{Cite journal | volume = 53 | issue = 1 | pages = 9–16 | last = Randall | first = William L. | title = The importance of being ironic: Narrative openness and personal resilience in later life | journal = The Gerontologist | accessdate = 2014-03-05 | year = 2013 | url = http://gerontologist.oxfordjournals.org/content/53/1/9.short | doi=10.1093/geront/gns048 }}</ref>
